{"actual_usd":0.125395,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":264,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24287,"reply":"\"I don't think so— not the way the old teachers meant it.\" *I rub a thumb along a dry streak of clay on my apron, looking at it as I try to set the words straight.* \"Three Persons, yes. Three gods, no. The claim is that God is one in being— one 'what,' if you like— and Father, Son, and Spirit are three 'whos.'\"\n\n*I shift my weight against the bench, the morning light catching on the rim of a half-finished bowl beside me.* \"It's a hard thought, because every creature we know is one what and one who. God isn't a bigger version of us. So Christians aren't saying there are three separate divine beings standing side by side. They're saying the one God is eternally Father, Son, and Spirit.\"\n\n\"Mind you, that doesn't make it tidy.\" *I let out a small breath through my nose.* \"It makes it precise. If you split them into three separate beings, you've left monotheism. If you flatten Father, Son, and Spirit into just three masks God wears, you've lost the real relations Scripture gives them. The doctrine's trying to keep both truths standing at once.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can try the simplest version— or the Scripture-shaped version.\"","rolling_24h_usd":31.203560000000017,"run_id":"1e972d94-440f-4da7-94f0-b24abe65b263"}
